  <h1>Categories of Genres</h1>
  <div>       
    <li>Action: Characterized by high-energy sequences, physical stunts, fights, and chases.
    <li>Adventure: Often involving journeys, quests, exploration, and exotic locations.</li>
    <li>Animation: A style of filmmaking (rather than a genre itself) that can incorporate any genre, using techniques like CGI, stop motion, or traditional drawing.</li>
    <li>Comedy: Primarily intended to make the audience laugh, with various subgenres like slapstick, dark comedy, and romantic comedy.</li>
    <li>Crime: Focuses on criminals, law enforcement, and the legal system, exploring themes of truth and justice.</li>
    <li>documentary: Non-fiction films or series providing factual information and narrativesabout real-life subjects or events.</li>
    <li>Drama: Centers on realistic characters and conflicts, focusing on emotional development and serious themes.</li>
    <li>Family/Kids: Content produced with a target audience of children or the entire family.</li>
    <li>Fantasy: Features speculative elements, often involving magic, mythical creatures, or otherworldly settings, inviting a suspension of reality.</li>
    <li>Historical: Set in a real historical time period, sometimes featuring fictional characters within an accurate setting.</li>
    <li>Horror: Seeks to elicit fear, dread, or disgust in the audience for entertainment purposes.</li>
    <li>Musical: Integrates songs and music as a significant part of the narrative.</li>
    <li>Mystery: Revolves around the unraveling of a secret or the solution of a crime or puzzle.</li>
    <li>Romance: Focuses on themes of love, passion, and the emotional relationship between main characters.</li>
    <li>Science Fiction (Sci-Fi): Explores the impact of actual, imagined, or potential science and technology, often set in the future or on other planets.</li>
    <li>Thriller: Designed to evoke excitement, suspense, and tension, often involving menacing situations or psychological suspense.</li>
    <li>War: Centers on military conflict and the human experiences within it.</li>
    <li>Western: Typically set in the American Old West, featuring cowboys, expansive
    landscapes, and conflict involving firearms.</li>
    <p>Streaming services and databases like The Movie Database (TMDB) often use a combination of these genres and specific keywords to help users find content.</p>
    </div>
